{"title_page": "Taita apalis", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Taita apalis\n| image = \n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn | author =BirdLife International | title=''Apalis fuscigularis'' | year=2017 | url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22713719/0 | accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n| genus = Apalis\n| species = fuscigularis\n| authority = [[Reginald Ernest Moreau|Moreau]], 1938\n| synonyms = ''Apalis thoracica fuscigularis''\n}}\n\nThe '''Taita apalis''' (''Apalis fuscigularis'') is a bird in the family [[Cisticolidae]] that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Taita Hills]] in [[Kenya]]. It was formerly considered to be a subspecies of the [[bar-throated apalis]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]]. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]]. It is one of the rarest birds in the world. The population is currently estimated at 300\u2013650 mature individuals though a survey  in 2009\u20132010 suggests the species has suffered a severe population decline in extent of its habitat and its population may now be as low as 60\u2013130 individuals. Most of the original forest has been cultivated or reforested with non-native timbers. Though little is known about this population crash as [[illegal logging]] and disturbance in the taita hills have been significantly reduced. However a serious drought in 2009  may have been a factor.  The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] considers this species to be [[critically endangered]] due to its tiny occupied range of {{convert|1.5|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} which is severely fragmented.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThis is a medium\u2013sized arboreal warbler at {{cvt|14|\u2013|16|cm}} long and {{cvt|10|\u2013|12|g}} in weight with dark grey upperparts slightly darker shade on wings and tail. The throat and breast is black and the underparts are white to off-white. The eye is silvery white. Call is a repeated ''pillipp, pillippp'' similar to that of the bar\u2013throated apalis while the song of the male is a loud ''chwee, chwee'' or ''chewk, chewk, chewk'', with which the female may duet, giving a high pitched song cheek.<ref>[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]] [[Lynx Edicions]], [[Barcelona]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=7398&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet.]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1513955}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:apalis, Taita}}\n[[Category:Apalis|Taita apalis]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1938|Taita apalis]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Cisticolidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Taita apalis\n| image = \n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn | author =BirdLife International | title=''Apalis fuscigularis'' | year=2017 | url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22713719/0 | accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n| genus = Apalis\n| species = fuscigularis\n| authority = [[Reginald Ernest Moreau|Moreau]], 1938\n| synonyms = ''Apalis thoracica fuscigularis''\n}}\n\nThe '''Taita apalis''' (''Apalis fuscigularis'') is a bird in the [[Cisticolidae]] family that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Taita Hills]] in [[Kenya]]. It was formerly considered to be a subspecies of the [[bar-throated apalis]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]]s. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]]. It is one of the rarest birds in the world. The population is currently estimated at 300\u2013650 mature individuals though a survey  in 2009\u20132010 suggests the species has suffered a severe population decline in extent of its habitat and its population may now be as low as 60\u2013130 individuals. Most of the original forest has been cultivated or reforested with non-native timbers. Though little is known about this population crash as [[illegal logging]] and disturbance in the taita hills have been significantly reduced. However a serious drought in 2009  may have been a factor.  The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] considers this species to be [[critically endangered]] due to its tiny occupied range of {{convert|1.5|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} which is severely fragmented.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThis is a medium\u2013sized arboreal warbler at {{cvt|14|\u2013|16|cm}} long and {{cvt|10|\u2013|12|g}} in weight with dark grey upperparts slightly darker shade on wings and tail. The throat and breast is black and the underparts are white to off-white. The eye is silvery white. Call is a repeated ''pillipp, pillippp'' similar to that of the bar\u2013throated apalis while the song of the male is a loud ''chwee, chwee'' or ''chewk, chewk, chewk'', with which the female may duet, giving a high pitched song cheek.<ref>[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]] [[Lynx Edicions]], [[Barcelona]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=7398&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet.]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1513955}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:apalis, Taita}}\n[[Category:Apalis|Taita apalis]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1938|Taita apalis]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Cisticolidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taita_apalis"}
{"title_page": "Annam prinia", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Prinia rocki\n| authority = Deignan, 1957\n}}\n\nThe '''Annam prinia''' (''Prinia rocki'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Cisticolidae]]. It and the [[Burmese prinia]] (''P. cooki'') were formerly lumped with [[Deignan's prinia]] (''P. polychroa'') as the brown prinia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Alstr\u00f6m|first=Per|last2=Rasmussen|first2=Pamela C.|last3=Sangster|first3=George|last4=Dalvi|first4=Shashank|last5=Round|first5=Philip D.|last6=Zhang|first6=Ruying|last7=Yao|first7=Cheng-Te|last8=Irestedt|first8=Martin|last9=Manh|first9=Hung Le|title=Multiple species within the Striated Prinia ''Prinia crinigera''-Brown Prinia ''P. polychroa'' complex revealed through an integrative taxonomic approach|journal=Ibis|language=en|volume=0|issue=ja|doi=10.1111/ibi.12759|issn=1474-919X|year=2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbw.com/species/brown-prinia-prinia-polychroa|title=Brown Prinia (Prinia polychroa)|website=www.hbw.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIt is found in the [[\u0110\u00e0 L\u1ea1t Plateau]] of the [[Annamite Range|Annamite Mountains]] in a small portion of southern [[Vietnam]] and eastern [[Cambodia]]. It is [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]] and has no known subspecies. It was split from ''P. cooki'' and ''P. polychroa'' following a phylogenetic study published in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | year=2020 | title=Grassbirds, Donacobius, Malagasy warblers, cisticolas, allies | work=IOC World Bird List Version 10.1 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/grassbirds/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=22 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:prinia, Annam}}\n[[Category:Prinia|Annam prinia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1957|Annam prinia]]\n\n\n{{Cisticolidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Prinia rocki\n| authority = Deignan, 1957\n}}\n\nThe '''Annam prinia''' (''Prinia rocki'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Cisticolidae]] family. It and the [[Burmese prinia]] (''P. cooki'') were formerly lumped with [[Deignan's prinia]] (''P. polychroa'') as the brown prinia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Alstr\u00f6m|first=Per|last2=Rasmussen|first2=Pamela C.|last3=Sangster|first3=George|last4=Dalvi|first4=Shashank|last5=Round|first5=Philip D.|last6=Zhang|first6=Ruying|last7=Yao|first7=Cheng-Te|last8=Irestedt|first8=Martin|last9=Manh|first9=Hung Le|title=Multiple species within the Striated Prinia ''Prinia crinigera''-Brown Prinia ''P. polychroa'' complex revealed through an integrative taxonomic approach|journal=Ibis|language=en|volume=0|issue=ja|doi=10.1111/ibi.12759|issn=1474-919X|year=2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbw.com/species/brown-prinia-prinia-polychroa|title=Brown Prinia (Prinia polychroa)|website=www.hbw.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIt is found in the [[\u0110\u00e0 L\u1ea1t Plateau]] of the [[Annamite Range|Annamite Mountains]] in a small portion of southern [[Vietnam]] and eastern [[Cambodia]]. It is [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]] and has no known subspecies. It was split from ''P. cooki'' and ''P. polychroa'' following a phylogenetic study published in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | year=2020 | title=Grassbirds, Donacobius, Malagasy warblers, cisticolas, allies | work=IOC World Bird List Version 10.1 | ur